Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 11:10 a.m. in  Manila .  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index slid 5.76, or 0.1
percent to 4,319.22. The measure is set for a 1.1 percent gain
this week, following two weeks of losses.  Metro Pacific Investments Corp. (MPI)  , a unit of  Hong
Kong â€™s First Pacific Co., fell 0.9 percent to 3.49 pesos, ending
a six-day rally. The company issued 2.03 billion common shares
to Metro Pacific Holdings Inc. upon the conversion of 6.6
billion pesos ($153 million) of convertible bonds.  Security Bank Corp. (SECB)   jumped 3.6 percent to 96.05
pesos, set for the sharpest gain since April 26, after President
Alberto Villarosa said its branch network will expand by 30
percent with the purchase of Premiere Development Bank.  To contact the reporter on this story:
